cashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fleming","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, from Middle English <i>fleming</i>. The word reflects a Norman French form of Old French <i>flamanc</i> ‘Fleming’, from the stem <i>flam-</i> + the ancient Germanic suffix <i>-ing</i>. In the Middle Ages there was considerable commercial intercourse between England and the Netherlands, particularly in the wool trade, and many Flemish weavers and dyers settled in England. This surname is also common in south and east Scotland and in Ireland, where it is sometimes found in the Gaelicized form <b>Pléamonn</b>.","German: variant of   Flemming  , cognate with 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Flemings","meanings":["English: plural form of   Fleming  .","Americanized form of Flemish <b>Vleminckx</b>: patronymic from <b>Vleminck</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle Dutch <i>vleminc</i>."]},{"name":"Flanders","meanings":["English: ethnic name from Middle English <i>Fla(u)ndres</i> ‘Flanders’, denoting someone from Flanders, a historical region covering parts of modern-day Belgium, France, and the Netherlands. Compare   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Fleeman","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flemming","meanings":["German: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle High German <i>vlaeminc</i>. People from Flanders spread throughout Germany, as well as England, in the Middle Ages as clothmakers and dyers.","English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flamenco","meanings":["Spanish: ethnic name from <i>flamenco</i> ‘Fleming, Flemish person’ (see   Fleming  )."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Fleming was born about 1385, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir William Fleming, was 21 and her mother, Fleming, was 21. She had at least 1 daughter with John Butler."},"et":{"Abt 1385–":"umbes 1385–Surnud","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1384–Male":"1384–Surnud","1406–1444":"1406–1444","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1444":"1444","1365":"1365","Abt 1385":"umbes 1385","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1406":"1406","Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beausey, Lancaster, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1385–":"noin 1385–Kuollut","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","1384–Male":"1384–Kuollut","1406–1444":"1406–1444","1365–Male":"1365–Kuollut","1365–Female":"1365–Kuollut","1444":"1444","1365":"1365","Abt 1385":"noin 1385","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1406":"1406","Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Beausey, Lancaster, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1385–":"environ 1385–Décédée","1385–Female":"1385–Décédée","1384–Male":"1384–Décédé","1406–1444":"1406–1444","1365–Male":"1365–Décédé","1365–Female":"1365–Décédée","1444":"1444","1365":"1365","Abt 1385":"environ 1385","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1406":"1406","Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Beausey, Lancaster, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Isabel Fleming est née environ 1385, à Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Sir William Fleming, avait 21 ans et sa mère, Fleming, avait 21 ans. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec John Butler."},"de":{"Abt 1385–":"um 1385–Verstorben","1385–Female":"1385–Verstorben","1384–Male":"1384–Verstorben","1406–1444":"1406–1444","1365–Male":"1365–Verstorben","1365–Female":"1365–Verstorben","1444":"1444","1365":"1365","Abt 1385